      <h1>
        <span class="highlight-container">AI Statement</span>
      </h1>
    </div>
    
    <div class="section-content" data-au="flex-container flex-vertical small-gap">
      <p>Artificial intelligence (AI) - whether you like it or not - is a game-changer. Just like when the Internet went mainstream, it's hard to see a future where AI is successfully pushed back into Pandora's box. It has the potential to revolutionize every industry and improve our lives in countless ways, but it also comes with real fears of mass unemployment, an expanded wealth divide, and even modern societal collapse. Combine these issues with the ecological side effects of data centers like large carbon footprints, egregious water usage, and far-from-minimal land use, and Terrabyte is squarely put between a rock and a hard place when it comes to using AI.</p>
	<p>On one hand, as a tech company, we are delighted with the possibilities of AI. Not the meme-creating, obnoxious misinformation engine it's becoming, but in being a digital Swiss-army knife. Especially when it comes to its ability to see patterns in huge datasets, build software tools with ease, and automate menial tasks - AI has the potential to bring about the death of doomscrolling, cyber-bullying, bloated tech companies, the enshittification of the Internet, inaccurate weather forecasts, clearing your inbox, even cancer and Alzheimers could become things of the past thanks to AI!</p>
	<p>On the other hand, we're a sustainability-focused company. The hypocrisy of using an environmentally-destructive tool to build environmentally-beneficial products is... questionable. When NFTs hit the market (and digital artwork was selling for millions), we saw the hypocrisy and decided to keep Pixel Planet Today designs off the blockchain. We really could have used those funds to further our eco projects, but the cost (carbon footprint, brand trust, uncertain profits) didn't seem to outweigh the benefit. While AI is a tool and NFTs are a platform (?) technology, the question remains the same: "should we use something that's proven to be bad for the environment in order to try to build products that attempt to help the environment?"</p>
<hr>
	<p>It's with these considerations that our stance has become,</p>
	<blockquote>If it's done for good, use the tool to accomplish more good. If it's not (or even for neutral outcomes), don't use it.</blockquote>
	<p>This stance will likely change as the technology evolves, but for now, we would describe our relationship with AI as a "cautious embrace." The technology itself, as it stands today, is not something we oppose, but the operational infrastructure of data centers, its use of copyrighted and uncredited work (hello, artist here!), its unregulated expansion, and the unseen cost of generating resource-intense content no one cares about - absolutely are. Just like with the Internet, it's a tool - and while humanity time and time again proves that it will use any tool it is given for evil, some gems will use them for good. We plan to be one of those players who use it to better the world.</p>
<h2>How we use AI</h2>
<p>Currently, our use of AI can be put into three categories: strategizing, researching, and development. We do not use AI to create graphics or other visual elements.</p>
      <p>At Terrabyte, we are committed to using AI in a way that is ethical, transparent, and aligned with our values of sustainability and social responsibility. We believe that AI should be developed and used in a way that minimizes its environmental impact. This means using energy-efficient algorithms and hardware, as well as considering the lifecycle of AI systems and their potential impact on the environment. We also believe that AI should be developed and used in a way that is transparent and accountable. This means being open about how AI systems are designed and how they make decisions, as well as being willing to take responsibility for any negative consequences that may arise from their use.</p>
      <p>Being anything other than a white, straight, cis male in a world tailored to white, straight, cis men can be difficult. And since our natural world is built on diversity, it's a no-brainer for us to support diversity found in our own species. <a class="text-link" href="/about-us/#the-team">Our squad</a> is made up of a wide array of individuals - we'd be proud to welcome even more unique talent to our team.</p>
      <p>We base all hiring decisions on who is the best fit for the role, our company, and our team. A position may include required qualifications, but if the best candidate doesn't meet these requirements (education, experience, etc.), we may consider other factors.</p>
      <p>Since "equality" is now a hot-button topic, before filing a complaint about our DEI policy, please refer to <a class="text-link" href="https://thediversitymovement.com/10-most-common-objections-dei-how-to-respond/" target="_blank">this doc</a>. If you would still like to file a complaint about this policy, you may email us using the link on our website's <a class="text-link" href="/#contact">homepage</a>.</p>
